 "55": {
  "edibility": "Verpa bohemica is considered toxic raw and potentially dangerous even after cooking. While some European traditions involve consumption after thorough parboiling with water changes, modern toxicology recognizes the presence of gyromitrin and related hydrazines that can cause serious neurological effects. Caution is strongly advised; repeated consumption poses cumulative toxicity risk.",
  "taste": "When prepared, early morels have a mild, delicate flavor reminiscent of true morels with subtle earthy notes. The taste is not particularly distinctive and does not justify the health risks associated with consumption.",
  "search": "Verpa bohemica fruits in early spring (March-April), typically 1-2 weeks before true morels (Morchella species), in moist floodplain woodlands, stream banks, and disturbed areas. Key distinguishing feature: the cap hangs freely from the stem (not attached at the base like true morels). Look-alikes include true morels and false morels (Gyromitra); verify the cap attachment point carefully.",
  "toxicity": {
   "severity": "severe",
   "symptoms": "Loss of muscular coordination (ataxia), tremors, dizziness, nausea, vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pain; in severe cases: seizures and loss of consciousness",
   "onset": "Typically 30 minutes to 3 hours after consumption; can be delayed up to 24 hours",
   "treatmentWindow": "Early medical intervention within 6-12 hours of exposure is critical; activated charcoal may be considered within the first hour if toxin absorption has not progressed significantly",
   "antidote": "No specific antidote exists; treatment is supportive care including fluid replacement, monitoring of neurological status, and management of seizures if they occur. Pyridoxine (vitamin B6) supplementation has been studied with mixed results in gyromitrin poisoning"
  }
 },
 "56": {
  "edibility": "Species are technically edible but accumulate significant cadmium, lead, and cesium-137 from soil and substrates due to their metallothionein-binding capacity. Caution is essential near roads, smelters, industrial zones, and areas affected by nuclear fallout. Regulatory limits exist: 0.050 mg/kg cadmium for cultivated mushrooms, up to 0.50 mg/kg in wild mushrooms.",
  "taste": "Suillus and Agaricus species have mild, typical mushroom flavor profiles. Both are valued culinary species when sourced from uncontaminated areas.",
  "search": "Find Suillus in pine plantations, coniferous forests, and roadsides; Agaricus in meadows and grasslands. Before harvest, assess soil quality and proximity to pollution sources, heavy traffic, or historical industrial sites. Test soil cadmium/lead levels if harvesting from uncertain areas; mushrooms growing on contaminated substrates will concentrate metals significantly above safe thresholds.",
  "toxicity": {
   "severity": "mild",
   "symptoms": "Cumulative heavy metal toxicity manifests as kidney damage (reduced function, proteinuria), neurological effects (tremors, cognitive decline, peripheral neuropathy), and potential carcinogenic effects over time",
   "onset": "Chronic onset over months to years of repeated consumption; symptoms appear insidiously as metals accumulate in organs",
   "treatmentWindow": "Heavy metal poisoning is best treated early in exposure accumulation. Chelation therapy initiated within days to weeks of acute high-dose exposure is most effective; chronic low-level exposure can be treated at any point but removal of contaminated foods is the primary intervention",
   "antidote": "DMSA (oral, first-line, FDA-approved for lead/mercury/arsenic) or EDTA (IV, FDA-approved for lead/cadmium) chelation therapy. DMSA achieves peak urinary metal excretion at 2 hours; EDTA at 4 hours. Treatment typically involves multiple cycles with breaks. Supportive care: maintain hydration, monitor kidney function. Severe cases require medical supervision to manage metal redistribution and prevent organ damage during treatment"
  }
 },
